🧾 Terraform Folder Structures (Quick Notes)  ------------------------------------->>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1️⃣ Flat Structure (Basic)

📁 Example:

project/
 ├── main.tf
 ├── variables.tf
 ├── outputs.tf
 └── provider.tf


✅ Best for: Small or demo projects
🟢 Pros: Simple to manage
🔴 Cons: Hard to scale when project grows

2️⃣ Modular Structure (Most Recommended ✅)

📁 Example:

project/
 ├── main.tf        # calls modules
 ├── variables.tf
 ├── outputs.tf
 ├── provider.tf
 └── modules/
      ├── ec2/
      │   ├── main.tf
      │   ├── variables.tf
      │   └── outputs.tf
      ├── s3/
      └── rds/


✅ Best for: Medium to large projects
🟢 Pros: Reusable, clean, scalable
🔴 Cons: Slightly more setup

3️⃣ Environment-Based Structure

📁 Example:

project/
 ├── envs/
 │    ├── dev/
 │    ├── test/
 │    └── prod/
 └── modules/
      ├── ec2/
      ├── s3/
      └── rds/
eg:-

my-terraform-project/
│
├── modules/
│   ├── ec2/
│   │   ├── main.tf
│   │   ├── variables.tf
│   │   └── outputs.tf
│   │
│   └── s3/
│       ├── main.tf
│       ├── variables.tf
│       └── outputs.tf
│
└── environments/
    ├── qa/
    │   ├── provider.tf
    │   ├── main.tf
    │   ├── variables.tf
    │   └── terraform.tfvars
    │
    ├── uat/
    │   ├── provider.tf
    │   ├── main.tf
    │   ├── variables.tf
    │   └── terraform.tfvars
    │
    └── prod/
        ├── provider.tf
        ├── main.tf
        ├── variables.tf
        └── terraform.tfvars


------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

One line summary of the whole flow of input values
tfvars → env/variables.tf → env/main.tf → module/variables.tf → module/main.tf → AWS resource
 value      declares it       passes it      receives it            uses it

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


✅ Best for: Multi-environment projects
🟢 Pros: Separate configs for each env
🔴 Cons: Bit more complex to manage

🏁 Best Practice

👉 Use Modular Structure (2️⃣) for most real-world and interview projects.
👉 Later, add Environment-Based setup for advanced multi-env projects.

++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
KEYWORDS IN TERRAFORM HCL LANGUAGE
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

1️⃣ provider → Defines which cloud (e.g., AWS, Azure, GCP) Terraform will use.
2️⃣ resource → Used to create and manage actual infrastructure (like EC2, S3).
3️⃣ variable → Declares inputs to make configurations reusable.
4️⃣ output → Displays or exports values after applying (like instance IP).
5️⃣ data → Reads existing resources without creating new ones.
6️⃣ module → Groups multiple resources into reusable components.
7️⃣ locals → Stores temporary or computed values.
8️⃣ depends_on → Ensures one resource is created before another.
9️⃣ lifecycle → Controls behavior (e.g., prevent_destroy, create_before_destroy).
🔟 provisioner → Runs commands/scripts after a resource is created.

